<!-- @author dawidl
     @depends General TCP/IP networking --><ns2267:section xmlns:ns2267="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.j2se.networking.introduction.introduction">
    
    <ns2268:title xmlns:ns2268="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Networking and Java</ns2268:title>
    
    <ns2269:para xmlns:ns2269="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        From the very beginning, the standard Java support technologies has seen networking
        as a central concern. This has resulted in Java being, at its core, better equipped to do
        any type of networked communication, than almost any other language in existence.
    </ns2269:para>
    <ns2270:para xmlns:ns2270="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        There are a few reasons for this networking convenience:
        <ns2271:itemizedlist xmlns:ns2271="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
            <ns2272:listitem xmlns:ns2272="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
                <ns2273:para xmlns:ns2273="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
                    Standardised <ns2274:emphasis xmlns:ns2274="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">low-level</ns2274:emphasis> networking (such as <ns2275:abbrev xmlns:ns2275="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">TCP</ns2275:abbrev>, <ns2276:abbrev xmlns:ns2276="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">UDP</ns2276:abbrev>)
                    implemented in a very intuitive and feature-rich manner, available on all platforms as part of the
                    Java runtime (from Cellular telephone, to Mainframe).
                </ns2273:para>
            </ns2272:listitem>
            <ns2277:listitem xmlns:ns2277="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
                <ns2278:para xmlns:ns2278="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
                    Cutting-edge <ns2279:emphasis xmlns:ns2279="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">networking-related frameworks</ns2279:emphasis>, such as <ns2280:emphasis xmlns:ns2280="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Jini</ns2280:emphasis> (automatic discovery and spontaneous interaction
                    between entities), <ns2281:emphasis xmlns:ns2281="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">JavaSpaces</ns2281:emphasis> (distributed / grid systems), <ns2282:emphasis xmlns:ns2282="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Java WebStart</ns2282:emphasis> (networked
                    application delivery and launching), <ns2283:emphasis xmlns:ns2283="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">RMI: Remote Method Invocation</ns2283:emphasis> (published, networked objects that
                    remove the complexity of networking altogether), etc.
                </ns2278:para>
            </ns2277:listitem>
            <ns2284:listitem xmlns:ns2284="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
                <ns2285:para xmlns:ns2285="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
                    <ns2286:emphasis xmlns:ns2286="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">A rich I/O framework</ns2286:emphasis> to easily assemble complex pipelines using the <ns2287:emphasis xmlns:ns2287="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">decorator</ns2287:emphasis> and 
                    <ns2288:emphasis xmlns:ns2288="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">pipes and filters</ns2288:emphasis> design patterns. This abstract framework is as at home on network
                    streams, as it is on files.
                </ns2285:para>
            </ns2284:listitem>
            <ns2289:listitem xmlns:ns2289="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
                <ns2290:para xmlns:ns2290="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
                    <ns2291:emphasis xmlns:ns2291="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Built-in multi-threading features</ns2291:emphasis> (essential, especially for networked servers) that help the developer
                    write safe, high-performance, concurrent code by making use of standard implementations for things such
                    as <ns2292:emphasis xmlns:ns2292="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">thread pools</ns2292:emphasis>, <ns2293:emphasis xmlns:ns2293="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">recurring tasks</ns2293:emphasis>, <ns2294:emphasis xmlns:ns2294="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">read/write locks</ns2294:emphasis>,
                    etc.
                </ns2290:para>
            </ns2289:listitem>
        </ns2271:itemizedlist>
    </ns2270:para>

</ns2267:section>